    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Cornelis de Schepper to Miklós Oláh (Brussels, 4 July
                    1535)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">He is sending Ghilino’s speech or letter for Oláh to
                            read and then show to the Queen. Camillo Ghilino does not want to make a
                            big deal of it, and he would not have written about it either, had he
                            not been encouraged to do so by Antonio de Leyva. According to Schepper,
                            no book can be so bad that it would be of no use, so Oláh should make
                            sure that the work does not disappear after the Queen has read it, and
                            he should write him what she thinks about it. Ulrich von Eytzing has
                            arrived, and Johan Weze writes that he will send Schepper’s clothes and
                            other things in a chest; Oláh should ask him what he knows about the
                            clothes and recommend Schepper to him. He wishes the bride and groom
                            much happiness. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Cornelius Scepperus Nicolao Olao suo <add corresp="Olahus"
                        type="insert">salutem</add>. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">Mitto ad Magnificentiam Vestram orationem seu epistolam cuius
                        <persName>illius Mediolanensis</persName>,<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.1">Camillo Ghilino, see <hi rend="smallcap">De Vocht</hi> 1961,
                        245.</note> ut illam legat, et postea ostendat <persName>reginali
                        maiestati</persName>, ad quam de eadem epistola scribo. Vult illam occultam
                    esse, neque refert magnopere, ut edatur, nisi quod arbitror instinctu et
                    admonitionibus domini <persName>Antonii de Layna</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.2">Antonio de Leyva.</note> marchionis Modoeciae<note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.3">He was Marquis of Pescara and
                        Commander-in-chief of the imperial army in the Duchy of Milan from 1525.
                        After Francesco II Sforza’s death (2 November, 1535), Emperor Charles V
                        appointed him Governor of Milan.</note> ipsum inductum, ut scriberet. In
                    summa nullus liber tam malus quin prosit, vide tamen, ne, cum regina eum
                    legerit, perdatur. Iudicium siquidem ea de re meum ad ipsum sum authorem
                    transcripturus. Et quia dominus <persName>Ulricus Eytzinger</persName><note
                        type="critic" xml:id="note.4">Ulrich von Eytzing (1499–1561), a courtier of
                        Queen Mary. According to De Vocht, it “seems to be merely a wrong spelling”,
                        and he was Ulric Ehinger, an international financial agent but he is wrong.
                        See <hi rend="smallcap">De Vocht</hi> 1961, 245.</note> advenit, et
                    reverendissimus <persName>Lundensis</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.5">Johan Weze.</note> ad me scripsit se quasdam vestes meas in
                    illius archam locasse huc ferendas una cum ipsius supellectile, quaeret ab eo
                    <?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?><?oxy_custom_end?>Magnificentia
                    Vestra, an de illis eisdem vestibus aliquid sciat, et me eidam commendabit.
                    Novis sponsis<note type="critic" xml:id="note.6">Probably Christina of Denmark
                        and Francesco II Sforza.</note> precor felicitatem. Bene vale. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3"><placeName>Bruxellae</placeName> IIII. Iulii XV<hi rend="super"
                        >c</hi>XXXV.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
